In Need for Speed: The Run, there's a race across America.
Review
The initially carefree ride, due to a series of completely unnecessary lazy lazy mistakes, turns into a routine morning ride to the shift.
The ambitions have largely been fulfilled, but it is no avail when no one seemed to want to do anything extra.
The new episode, subtitled The Run, attracted high expectations before it was released.
He promised to move the years-long Need for Speed racing series again in a new direction, appearing from playable previews as a game that might not just be in the number of numbers in the genre of action racing.
We were also curious to see how the inserted passages would turn out, in which the main character would get out of the car and run his own way.
But, as is customary with the NFS series, much is a bit different in the end than we expected.
These are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole is dragging down some unnecessary errors that have been appearing in the series for more or less for several years.
So it's not really even mistakes, but rather a manifestation of some incomprehensible laziness of developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are inducted into a story whose main character, Jack, has some personal problems and is offered as a solution to participate in an illegal race across America.
You get behind the wheel on the West Coast in San Francisco and your job is to arrive first in New York.
The idea brings with it some interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then more than fifty races.
It follows that each race is run on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
It doesn't feel for a moment that the game would offer the same thing all the time.
In addition, some of the backgrounds are very pretty to look at, even though the technical level of graphics matches the previous episodes of the series.
So it's not a big deal.
But driving across the desert, the autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains feels very pleasurable visually.
In addition, the races are enhanced from time to time by some atypical element.
In the desert, for example, you get stuck in a sandstorm that reduces visibility considerably.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you have to be careful not to be swallowed by an avalanche.
Alongside this, the individual races are pretty well in a row.
There are only a few types of them, but that's enough.
For a while you try to overtake the required number of rivals (basically a classic race), then catch up again (the classic duel with the stopwatch) and then there is a duel with a single opponent waiting for you.
This is still the police who make your whole effort even further unpleasant in the making.
The new feature are the passages outside the car.
Rather, it's just interactive animations, with Jack mostly fleeing from someone and you have to help him do it by printing the right buttons in the right moments.
Nothing complicated.
But it comes as a surprise that there are far fewer of these passages in the game than you would have expected (specifically perhaps only three).
In the end, however, it is to the benefit of the cause, because this element has no chance of becoming annoying and, in the context of the above, thus ranks among the elements that make the game more interesting.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of previous episodes.
That means it's definitely not something these days, but you can't say it's a downswing.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you will have to look elsewhere.
But the more acclaimed racing of the local driving model still suits quite well, even though we could find a better one for the competition.
So far, therefore, everything is in perfect order.
But problems are starting to emerge after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is no longer very well.
We don't expect a game of this type to count the complex deformations and collisions, but if you have no idea before any crash into any object how your car will behave, then I guess everything is not quite right.
Typically, when you're overtaking or passing cars in normal traffic, you'll sometimes just lick each other lightly, but at other times in an almost identical situation, your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even just fuck off.
Thanks to the reboots system, it doesn't particularly matter, but it will make you feel special.
The reboggarts are designed so that if you smash or go far out of the track, the game will throw you back to the last clue point on the track.
But there are only five of the reboots available in each race.
If you exhaust them, you have to start the race again from the beginning.
It is, therefore, a kind of aid in case something goes wrong than being able to rely on them in a downright way.
Sometimes, however, even the reboots don't help, solving them only when the need to learn the given section of the race from memory.
The big ailment of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns need to be driven in a specific way, otherwise you simply can't fit into them.
Other times, you will meet "civil" cars in the same configuration at a given location, whether you arrive there first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
It will be particularly annoyed in situations where you see the opponent driving easily between the two oncoming cars in front of you, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake them.
It doesn't matter when you reach them, because it's "calculated" so that the situation is always happening just in front of your nose.
Rivals have another advantage.
Throughout the playing time, you will come across several places where, again, no matter what time, you are always overtaken by the same opponent in the same place.
It hits the most in the end of the game on the long bridge, where you drive in the opposite direction.
The opponent must obviously get there in front of you at any price.
When he rides in front of you, he's making you worse the overview of oncoming cars, so you'll probably get a few times over there at first.
It is possible to understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-fuelled, but the execution is so obvious that it will quickly disgust you with reliability.
And it's a shame, because despite the simple driving model, the playing is fun and, in places, so action-packed that sometimes you literally can't keep track of where what's flying.
And it doesn't really matter whether it's the credit of a concept with fifty unique tracks, gearing up races so that boredom doesn't stand a chance or anything else.
An unconventional idea is to replace cars during races.
You have to be careful of the gas stations by the roads, because that's where you can change the car, even though in the vast majority of cases you can do with what you're having right now.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are suitable for urban areas, heavy American highway bumps and exotic supersports for technical riding, for example, on winding mountain roads.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand with the challenge mode, which are races in individual locations you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points in your profile, which is common to the challenges and the story.
For obtaining a higher level of driver, different items are unlocked: from the cars to the background for the profile.
It is also again linked to the online feature Autolog, which, among other things, compares your achieved results with other players and provides additional community functions.
One of the other hard-to-understand kicks is the situation of the last race in the story.
With your car you will get to the subway tunnel (be) where you are in the dark by the rails (be).
The number between 150 and 200 km/h (let) you flash on the speedometer, and in that, a subway train comes in from behind and uncompromisingly scraps you.
In the newsroom, we will probably still have a few more discussions about whether no one really thought a little when creating the game, or whether the authors think of us as really such a big jerk.
The technical side of the game is nothing extra, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and, in a few cases, even great.
It freezes so much that in some of the more tense imaging drops, in some cases quite tragically.
But it mainly concerns crashes with more participants, when smooth imaging would no longer be of any use to you.
The sound side is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an attempt to appeal to the widest range of rather younger audiences, the soundtrack from the category of "every dog a different village" was created, but it can be assumed that, because of listening to music, the game will probably not be bought.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is so highly embarrassed.
If the game were to avoid completely unnecessary errors, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best part of the NFS in the last few years.
