How tour prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia at the time: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At the time, travel agencies overwhelmingly sold only trips to the socialist bloc countries, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists thus travelled on holiday to the sea to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea by the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and Hungary (the Balaton).
The bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was also possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime went to the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the time of socialism was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely individually even within socialist countries.
In case a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to, for example, Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise the individual way was not possible.
Travel agents at the time also offered tours to the West, but it was necessary to queue up overnight with a sleeping bag or have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to "politically unreliable people" who were thus unable to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without the foreign exchange promise it was not possible to raise funds (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
However, the most frequently spent the Czechs vacationing in the Czech Republic, resulting in a large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs acquired and this custom survives to this day.
The travel of the Czechs has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which we are no longer aware of today, is that it was not possible to travel freely to us in the most popular Croatia at the moment, as it was part of what was then Yugoslavia.
Early in the 1990s, the visa requirement was lifted to neighbouring Western European countries, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits to Austria's Vienna or Germany in particular.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to at least take a look there for a while.
In Paris, for example, the tours of Czechs slept in parks in tents, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a guesthouse.
A typical feature of Czechs' travel at this time was to drive their own food, canned food, salami, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown, which our tourists were able to buy the Western currency freely after many of the years.
But our standard of living, and with it, the average salaries were rising, resulting in another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agents have started to regularly prepare tours with charter air connections since 1997, making air tours incredibly cheaper thanks to the possibility of contracting quantity discounts compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs already had visa-free travel to virtually all developed countries of the world, except the US, which continued to make our travel easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel came as early as 2000, when, thanks to considerable demand, the first direct charter flight to exotica was dispatched from the Czech Republic, it was to Thailand.
From this year, direct charters fly out with Czech tourists to warm far-off countries, this winter will be flown directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are now visited by around 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which is symbolized by our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US revoked visas for Czech tourists, and thus our country was finally among the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time in their history (50.3%) and spent more than 15,000 on one foreign holiday, including the cost of the stay, for the first time in their history. CZK per person.
