During the first year of Mario López Valdez's government, unemployment and unreliability rose in Sinaloa, with falling foreign investment, and with them the economy
2011 will be written in the economic history of Sinaloa. This is the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, which itself is called the government of change. This government has brought with it high expectations in terms of economic progress, however, due to adverse climatic conditions at the start of the year, no growth was observed and there was even a decline in the main economic development indicators.
Low February temperatures caused millions of losses in agriculture, curtailed the growth potential for the state economy, responsible for a 3.6% reduction in economic activity in the first semester of this year. In the area of agriculture, there was a historic 31.16% decline, which disrupted the dynamism of other economic sectors as well.
According to the damage report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, the damage was recorded on 582,835 hectares of cultivated land, of which 78.03% were completely destroyed and partial damage was found for the remaining 21.07%. The main crops destroyed include vegetables, corn and peas.
The drop in economic activity until November was caused by a constant rise in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute for Statistical and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state recorded an increase in the first three quarters. Between January and March, the 55,053 Sinaloa residents were not employed, representing an unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment rose to 5.28%, and between July and August, average unemployment continued to rise, reaching 6.19%, representing around 74,000 unemployed. Compared to the first quarter, the number of unemployed people increased by 18,969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment during the year in the state of Sinaloa is due to multiple factors. According to Gerard López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences at the UAS, the rise of unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on steps that have been taken at public policy level.
"We are seeing rising unemployment, which is related to various factors. These include, among other things, the loss of liquidity in the market due to resource constraints on the basis of legislation passed by the Congress in the context of the fight against money laundering. It is not easy for people who illegally seize up with dollars to earn them, invest them or use them for something," he stressed.
Stopping migration
López Cervantes said the demographic factor was also involved in the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people going abroad to work, to the United States, has been reduced, both for reasons of difficult entry and then because, even if these people cross the country, it is difficult for them to get a job. So people stay and demand work from our state, so unemployment is rising," he said.
Unreliability
The analysis of the Sinaloa labour market is also deteriorating due to the growing unreliability that prevails in the area of working conditions. According to the National Institute for Statistical and Democracy, 60.38% of the employed population in the state works without paying benefits to the Social Security Administration.
Unemployment and unreliability are joined by other features of the labour market, such as low pay. In this administrative territory, the lowest salaries are from across the country, as reported by the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Labor Secretariat and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of the Sinaloa working state was 5,352 pesetas by September, well below the national average, which is at 7,375 pesetas.
Shortening foreign direct investment
Along with a decline in economic activity and an increase in unemployment, the sharpest drop in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years was also recorded in 2011. According to the Ministry of Finance, between January and June, foreign direct investment amounted to $630,6970, a decrease of 87.74% compared to $5,143,312 for the same period the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the State Government lists investments of 17,280 million pesetas per year. These investments were mainly directed to services businesses.
Dolv
In the context of the scenario of the downturn in the economy, the government asked the state's congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion peso. This would be earmarked for investment in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas to revitalise the economy. The local congress approved a loan of 2,600 million peso. By November, no debt gains had been recorded, in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
According to business sector representatives, the first year of the government of Mario López Valdares pointed out the lack of management of the government's management capabilities.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transforming Industry, said that in 2011 there was a lack of aligning the will of individual sectors, including the state's very government.
"The development of the Sinaloa economy was really tiny during this year. We need to work intensively to get back the land we lost this year. We must redouble our efforts in 2012, a lack of harmonisation of the efforts of all of us and, in particular, the right and synchronised functioning of this new government. Hopefully next year will be much better," he said.
The Grease of the Economy
Loredo López said that the frost-welling events at the start of the year halted the state economy and curtailed its development and growth.
"Favorbital economic movements were caused by a number of events, including frosts. One of the main consequences was a slowdown in the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to restore the dynamism that would allow an acceptable level of movement for processes, products, and services to be achieved. That is why we were well below the expected forecasts at the end of the year," he said.
Redefining the mission
According to Teodor Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employers' Confederation of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, the state should be pushed to more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we observe that we are in the works. We believe that a long-term plan needs to be prepared in which the objectives and economic direction of the state would be redefined, because it is important that the full potential of the material and human resources that Sinaloa has is mobilised," he said.
The work ahead
President Coparmex stressed the importance of setting a vision for the future to better guide the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in various areas, with some progress in the area of economic development, but it is important to create a long-term plan," he said.
He said the current administration had shown progress in public policy leadership.
"There are elements that make it possible to claim that the government is trying to be welcoming. I can say that the work done is to be seen here and I believe that the Government is aware that there is also a lot of work ahead of us," he said.
