"The trip to Costa Rica is a dream that is becoming a reality"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band was ready to offer one of the best gigs at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We have waited more than 20 years, but the group itself assures that the opportunity for them to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
This is what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively to Viva from Brazil last week, said.
The group is located on the South American continent as part of a tour to celebrate 20 years of existence and will be at a unique stop in Central America on Sunday 20.
He will perform this day at the National Stadium from 7:30 p.m. with the angel band The X and the national musicians of Las Robertas.
This is a sample from the interview, the full transcript of which can be found on the website La Nación on the internet.
It's a dream come true for your Costa Rican supporters. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realise what your fans are experiencing?
The journey to Costa Rica is also our dream, which is becoming a reality.
In South and Central America, we've barely been the second time and the experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on holiday. It's a beautiful country, and I believe we'll be able to stay here for a few days.
So we're so happy to bring you our music.
I ask because they literally adore the group here, the fans are experiencing these days of preparation very intensely.
What do you say to your most ghastly supporters?
Thank you for standing by us for years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that it took us so long.
Some people already refer to the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does it give you more pressure?
Some of the biggest shows we've put on in the last 21 years have been made in a matter of weeks.
We have performed some great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope to get into shape for a concert in Costa Rica.
In fact, we're really looking forward to the concert.
We love this country, we like to surf, we like to like the jungle. For both activities, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves to surf?
We have a lot of friends of surplators, and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo. The waves here are incredible.
My friends go to surf Costa Rica or Nicaragua, or Mexico. These are the best surfing spots. And so we found out about Costa Rica, through people who love to surf.
If we look at your tour, you've set up a huge show with many songs.
What did you plan to present in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, we have no limitations on what we can't do.
We will try to put on the best show possible with a variety of tracks. We will try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What for?
I think in part it's because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to choose which songs we'll play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven't played for a long time, we focus on them and we're also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that maybe we've already forgotten about it.
So the show is more interesting for us, which is why I think it is more interesting for people.
With this tour you celebrate 20 years of artistic career.
When you look back, is it hard to believe everything you've accomplished?
Yes, I'm sure.
First, I think that none of us could have imagined that we would be in one big rock band and that we would stay in it for more than 20 years. Sounds like a dream.
We realise how much we have been given and are touched by the fact that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and like to make music.
We are fortunate to be able to look at the places we have always wanted.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were an important part of the origin of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honour for us to be a part of this group in which the great greats are represented.
The people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It's surprising when a movement emerges from a group of friends, it doesn't happen very often.
A group emerges from time to time in the city, but it is far less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at once.
We are proud of this and we are honoured to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we still play with some of them.
Last year we were at the Alice in Chains festival and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are fortunate that these are all our friends and we are honoured to be a part of this movement that was formed in Seattle.
It's also very unusual for a group like yours to keep together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a much longer period of age than the usual duration of the group.
I think, first of all, we are all lucky to be still in this world and, secondly, the fact that we are constantly interested in each other plays a part of the role.
We are all close friends and, as a result, we have managed to open up musical paths that leave everyone with sufficient freedom to experiment themselves.
We trust each other, we value each other's music, and I don't think it could be better.
Your relationship to the word fame was not easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find the balance?
The way we grew, it was gradually getting easier to find a balance.
We try not to go too much on tour because it's very easy to fall into this trap of the crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for the music, you remind yourself that you have to respect the music and what you have given it. You mustn't get carried away by being famous, rock stars. This was never really of interest to either of us.
How do you remember the next Mother Love Bone project?
I think we were writing great songs and at the beginning it was something spectacular.
We had been around as a band for three years and we never released an album until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. Most importantly, even today we are friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started out in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at the photos, I remember Andy being unbelievable, how much I laughed with him. It was always a pleasure to work with him, to laugh, to talk about music or football and much more.
She was an incredible person and we miss her so much.
The national band Las Robertas will be commissioned to launch a show in Costa Rica.
