Yes, the production sent us videos with several designs and we liked this group the most. That's why we're wondering what Las Robertas will offer live and they need to be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he adds the first thing he thinks of.
Who is influencing you as a bassist?
Lots of people.
First up, I'm first thought of Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramon, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There's so many, I could talk all night about the bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge, even though it is no longer in vogue?
I think we've all always felt a little separate from the word grunge.
When you say grunge, I imagine the groups I mentioned as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that were created at the same time. And if music is still this valid today, it's something great because it's music worth listening to and the bands like Mudhoney are playing better music today than ever before.
At the beginning, your music had a slightly gloomy character and is now more positive.
What is behind this change?
That's interesting because I have a feeling that there are a few songs in the new album that are lighter, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe, which are considered very gloomy, although they may come off as positive.
With both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried, and they're songs deeply dark.
I think when you grow up and have some trauma in your life, you lose someone in your family or boyfriend, these things start to affect your arts and music, and these two songs represent this to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make gloomy music.
