Mexico's health insurance institute launches research into the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance is conducting research to discover the gene responsible for obesity of children and adolescents. Research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to detect a gene causing obesity in children and young people. Research called "Obesity Genetics in Children and Teenagers" will make it possible to get results on overweight.
In a report by the head of the Biochemistry Research Medical Unit from the Specialized Hospital of the 21st Century National Health Center, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been set up.
This team relies on the support of specialists and pupils of postgraduate studies from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research can also involve the general public, having or not authorized. People can come to the participating IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where tests will be performed by the teens each reindeer from 8 a.m.
He stressed that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (Mexican State) and from 8. October, this activity is also carried out at the Unlandalcóyolt Sports Centre (East of the Mexican State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children are obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research was to identify the components and importance of genetics in terms of obesity development and to trace to Mexican children and young people to risk factors and thus prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim was to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between the age of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and a family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He specified that every Saturday, all participants are being given anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), pulp, blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglicerides, cholesterol, insulin are determined, and genes are studied (the genes involved in developing childhood obesity are sought to be identified).
Cruz López said this research reflected the concerns of health professionals over the alarming increase in child scales.
'Health polls conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, there was a 77% increase in obesity in boys alone and 47% for girls. There has also been a dramatic increase in the case of overweight," said the IMSS expert.
He said that one of the reasons for the search for indicators was the assumption that the country's population was different from that of other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% of Indian-American genetic makeup, 30% European and 5% African. This is reflected in the genes responsible for the formation of diabetes and the overweight.
He explained that, in general, the genetics of obesity are commonly explained as an inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calorie) and stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they will receive an overall assessment of the condition of the children, thus determining whether they exhibit any known overweight or obesity.
He said that even the presence of dark-coloured wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm indicated the likelihood that the individual would suffer from metabolic problems and pre-curklar conditions.
The information is still confidential, with doctors handing it in writing to their parents and explaining to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they have to make to avoid the disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three major ingredients that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle that means a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV all day, and using means of transport instead of walking for short distances.
Overweight is also due to great caloric intake, i.e. greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content, and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
In Asphalt from UNAM there will be no potholes
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the Chemical Faculty of UNAM, forms modified asphalts with polymers to create a mixture with better functionality, independently of climatic conditions and temperature
If the cobbles were properly cared for, there would be no need to repair nearly 200,000 potholes after each rainy season in the Metropolitan area of Valle de México, Rafael Herrera hijacker, a scientist at the Chemical Faculty (FQ) at the UNAM, who also added that if the design and maintenance of asphalt paving were adequate, there would be a significant reduction in potholes, or even be able to be removed altogether.
In his lecture, the Technology Cue of Colour, he delivered in the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory under his direction was developing modified polymer asphalt asphalt, creating a mixture with similar characteristics to the asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country. This would improve functionality and reduce the creation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the hardest part of the oil, is a cluster of hydrocarbon molecules, a molecular molecular mass called asphalten, and others with low molecular weights called mortars. Together, they give the asphalt a typical visco-elastic character.
The viscoleastic character of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees has a high viscosity and is almost in firm state at 50 degrees, while at low temperatures asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperatures, the chemical engineering expert pointed out.
A University of Chemics scientist observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible paving, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers are the asphalt insert, made up of small stones topped in asphalt and then compressed.
He stressed that every stone that forms the liner is to be bathed in asphalt.
When cars pass or when you create pressure, it is so possible to disinheritate the forces in the pavement well.
If it was modified asphalt, they would break up even better, the chemical engineer believes.
He added that the asphalt insert was the last layer called the cloak, made up of fine rock, that is, the sand also encased in the asphalt.
As this layer will come into contact with the rims of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and ensure the friction of the road.
As part of the cobbles, it will be subjected to a heavy load, the casing must be of sufficient thickness and care must be taken to the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to be kept in mind. Water in particular has a major impact on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the terrain is damp, the water travels inwards and it is difficult to get out, this causes all layers of pavement to be softened and thus the formation of potholes.
He explained that the film of the cladding was the first to be damaged during the potholes, and only then did the asphalt insert be damaged. However, the damage does not occur at one point, but it is a gradual process that should be stopped at the first signs using the appropriate maintenance programmes.
As a member of the National Researchers' System, he also explained that the load on vehicles is another important factor in creating potholes, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of paving must correspond to the load of vehicles and must ensure that this burden is not exceeded. Only in this way can we prevent the frequent emergence of potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there is still a lot of work to do when it comes to asphalt, and the research is at the beginning. For example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and make it easy to repair potholes without having to use high temperatures, are worth mentioning.
