The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The undersea pipe is made of steel fitted with a concrete shell to be protected from the anchors of the naval vessels.
It rests at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
In its construction, it was necessary to avoid the minefields from the time of World War II.
"For security reasons, almost a hundred had to be removed or destroyed," says Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase the measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipes themselves are a long metal snake weighing like the 242 Eiffel Tower, which is not interrupted anywhere by the valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it when the Swedes were little greedily to see the Russian state-owned company permanently settling off their coast.
"In the event of a defect, we will stop the gas passage in less than 1 minute," Jens Müller states.
In the event of a leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, after all, the welds were designed to create a leak once every 100,000 years.
The inspection of the state of the pipeline from the outside is carried out by an underwater robot towed by the ship, while the interior of the pipeline is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
